    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1981-11-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1981-11-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="100"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d100">
                <head>100. Memorandum From Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_HAM_1"
                        >Haig</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_RRW_1">Reagan</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d100fn1">Source: Reagan Library, Executive
                        Secretariat, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss>: Country File, <gloss
                            target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss> (11/6/1981–11/6/1981). Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1981-11-09">November 9, 1981</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Release of Soviet Dissidents</item>
                </list>
                <p>The <gloss target="#t_CSCE_1">CSCE</gloss> meeting in Madrid could conclude this
                    fall, if we can reach agreement on the mandate for a conference on military <rs
                        corresp="rec6knwDvEj45PVa0" type="topic">confidence-building measures</rs>
                    in Europe (<gloss target="#t_CDE_1">CDE</gloss>), balanced by <rs
                        corresp="recVSPQM8CicmOme2" type="topic">human rights</rs> provisions that
                    go beyond the Helsinki Final Act of 1975. This gives us an opportunity to try to
                    get some people out of the <gloss target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss>. Specifically,
                    we should seek release of <persName corresp="#p_SA_2">Shcharanskiy</persName>,
                    the jailed Jewish dissident and Helsinki monitor, whose wife you met, and
                        <persName corresp="#p_SA_1">Sakharov</persName>, the exiled physicist who
                    has been critical of the Soviet regime. If this proves impossible, we could
                    settle for one or the other, or a larger number of lesser-known dissidents.</p>
                <p>The incentive for the Soviets to agree to this is that we, in turn, would reduce
                    somewhat our demands for language on <rs corresp="recVSPQM8CicmOme2"
                        type="topic">human rights</rs> in the concluding document at Madrid. We
                    would thus achieve “balance”: in part by the significant political—and
                    humanitarian—symbolism of getting people released. We would meet Congressional
                    concerns that we won’t get enough out of Madrid on <rs
                        corresp="recVSPQM8CicmOme2" type="topic">human rights</rs>, and we would
                    demonstrate that the Administration’s approach to <rs
                        corresp="recVSPQM8CicmOme2" type="topic">human rights</rs> produces more
                    results than rhetoric.</p>
                <p>I will raise this initially with Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_DA_2"
                        >Dobrynin</persName>; then, if the Soviets agree to talk, Ambassador Max
                    Kampelman will pursue it with his Soviet counterpart in Madrid. The discussions
                    would be kept totally secret. While we will resist any Soviet effort to get a
                    quid pro quo beyond the <gloss target="#t_CSCE_1">CSCE</gloss> context, we will
                    tell them that this gesture would improve the tone of our relationship.</p>
                <p>This is a long shot, but well worth trying. I will of course keep you informed of
                    any developments.</p>
            </div>
